00:00:39.510 --> 00:00:43.350
and it's about a question,
which I raised last time,

00:00:43.350 --> 00:00:46.044
which has kind of been a
question puzzling philosophers

00:00:46.044 --> 00:00:47.910
from the beginning of philosophy,

00:00:47.910 --> 00:00:50.493
which is how do you get
from something to nothing?

00:00:51.390 --> 00:00:53.700
At some point there
wasn't a Ukrainian nation

00:00:53.700 --> 00:00:56.447
and at some point there
is a Ukrainian nation.

00:00:56.447 --> 00:00:58.020
How does that happen?

00:00:58.020 --> 00:01:01.590
How do you get social forms
to come into existence

00:01:01.590 --> 00:01:03.840
that didn't exist before?

00:01:03.840 --> 00:01:07.080
It's a really interesting question.

00:01:07.080 --> 00:01:10.503
And you can ask it with other
social formations as well.

00:01:11.760 --> 00:01:13.290
There didn't used to be classes,

00:01:13.290 --> 00:01:15.090
but now we don't have any difficult--

00:01:15.090 --> 00:01:16.230
I don't mean the classes that you're in.

00:01:16.230 --> 00:01:18.570
I mean, social classes,
right? Economic classes.

00:01:18.570 --> 00:01:19.920
Those didn't use to exist either,

00:01:19.920 --> 00:01:22.350
but now we don't have
much trouble identifying,

00:01:22.350 --> 00:01:23.520
oh, he's middle class.

00:01:23.520 --> 00:01:26.270
Actually we're in America,
so everybody's middle class.

00:01:27.660 --> 00:01:28.920
Thinking that everyone's middle class

00:01:28.920 --> 00:01:31.800
is part of the class struggle,
I'm sure you know that.

00:01:31.800 --> 00:01:33.180
So if you all think you're middle class,

00:01:33.180 --> 00:01:34.530
that means you're already in, okay.

00:01:34.530 --> 00:01:36.270
Sorry that wasn't our
subject today at all.

00:01:36.270 --> 00:01:38.190
We're gonna move back to nations.

00:01:38.190 --> 00:01:39.023
Although the Marxists

00:01:39.023 --> 00:01:40.740
are gonna get a little shout out later on

00:01:40.740 --> 00:01:42.510
because actually Marxists
were some of the first people

00:01:42.510 --> 00:01:44.580
to think about the nation.

00:01:44.580 --> 00:01:46.500
But when we're thinking
about this social form

00:01:46.500 --> 00:01:50.130
of the nation, what makes
it particularly tricky

00:01:50.130 --> 00:01:55.130
is that the nation, once it
exists, lays claim to the past.

00:01:55.860 --> 00:01:58.620
So the nation didn't always exist

00:01:58.620 --> 00:02:01.560
but once it comes into existence,

00:02:01.560 --> 00:02:04.470
it tells a story about the past

00:02:04.470 --> 00:02:08.853
and the story that the nation
tells about the past is wrong.

00:02:10.800 --> 00:02:12.000
That's the short version.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:14.850
It tells a story which clears out the past

00:02:14.850 --> 00:02:17.910
and that story calls itself history.

00:02:17.910 --> 00:02:21.300
Although it's not really
history, it calls itself history.

00:02:21.300 --> 00:02:25.230
And so this new social form has a story

00:02:25.230 --> 00:02:29.130
about how it's very old and
that confusion is confusion

00:02:29.130 --> 00:02:32.220
that basically everyone
lives their whole life with.

00:02:32.220 --> 00:02:33.270
Unless you're American.

00:02:33.270 --> 00:02:35.100
If you're American,
then your national story

00:02:35.100 --> 00:02:36.960
is that you're new and you're fresh

00:02:36.960 --> 00:02:38.130
and you're all about the future,

00:02:38.130 --> 00:02:40.200
which is ironic because
the American nation

00:02:40.200 --> 00:02:43.050
is actually comparatively
speaking, quite old.

00:02:43.050 --> 00:02:44.040
It's funny, right?

00:02:44.040 --> 00:02:46.110
It's actually older than
most of the European nations,

00:02:46.110 --> 00:02:49.290
but don't tell the Europeans
and don't tell the Americans,

00:02:49.290 --> 00:02:50.700
'cause that would mess everybody up.

00:02:50.700 --> 00:02:55.700
So the trick though is
that the nation is modern,

00:02:56.010 --> 00:02:58.410
but it lays claim to the past

00:02:58.410 --> 00:03:02.520
in a way which if we ourselves
are at all nationally minded

00:03:02.520 --> 00:03:07.050
and many of us probably are,
feels comfortable and right.

00:03:07.050 --> 00:03:09.840
And that makes it very hard
to answer this question

00:03:09.840 --> 00:03:11.430
of where the nation came from

00:03:11.430 --> 00:03:14.313
because the nation is
already giving you an answer.

00:03:15.150 --> 00:03:18.210
The nation comes equipped with an answer.

00:03:18.210 --> 00:03:20.490
It comes equipped in the most banal

00:03:20.490 --> 00:03:21.930
and obvious practical sense,

00:03:21.930 --> 00:03:24.810
which you've already encountered
in your lives probably,

00:03:24.810 --> 00:03:26.520
which is that as you're educated,

00:03:26.520 --> 00:03:27.930
as you go through elementary school,

00:03:27.930 --> 00:03:29.340
middle school, high school,

00:03:29.340 --> 00:03:32.130
if you're in anything like a
national educational system,

00:03:32.130 --> 00:03:34.110
you're given answers to these questions,

00:03:34.110 --> 00:03:37.380
which seem self-evident as
to where the nation came from.

00:03:37.380 --> 00:03:39.960
But of course, there's a
circular phenomenon here,

00:03:39.960 --> 00:03:42.540
which is that once there's
a national consciousness,

00:03:42.540 --> 00:03:44.160
once there's a national identity,

00:03:44.160 --> 00:03:48.210
then the educational system
takes on a national character

00:03:48.210 --> 00:03:51.690
and then reproduces that national
consciousness and identity

00:03:51.690 --> 00:03:54.690
in a way which then starts
to seem unproblematic

00:03:54.690 --> 00:03:56.370
and commonsensical.

00:03:56.370 --> 00:03:58.680
So there's a circular quality about this,

00:03:58.680 --> 00:04:00.600
which is very hard to break out of

00:04:00.600 --> 00:04:02.490
when you're seven years old.

00:04:02.490 --> 00:04:05.130
I mean, I'm sure all of you
are smarter than average

00:04:05.130 --> 00:04:07.140
and each one of you is smarter
than the person next to you.

00:04:07.140 --> 00:04:08.820
I'm aware of this, you're Yale students,

00:04:08.820 --> 00:04:11.700
but when you were seven, you pro--

00:04:11.700 --> 00:04:13.260
Okay, six.

00:04:13.260 --> 00:04:15.690
When you were six, you probably
weren't raising your hand

00:04:15.690 --> 00:04:18.300
and talking about the constructed
character of national--

00:04:18.300 --> 00:04:19.500
Right? You probably weren't.

00:04:19.500 --> 00:04:21.840
You were probably, I don't know.

00:04:21.840 --> 00:04:23.430
Correct me, but I imagine

00:04:23.430 --> 00:04:25.500
that what they told you about
the past in your schools,

00:04:25.500 --> 00:04:27.060
you were probably either ignoring it

00:04:27.060 --> 00:04:29.700
or somehow taking it in
to some extent, right?

00:04:29.700 --> 00:04:32.317
Thank you for those nods.
That's very affirming.

00:04:32.317 --> 00:04:36.240
So the obvious way that this happens

00:04:36.240 --> 00:04:37.170
is the institutional way.

00:04:37.170 --> 00:04:38.490
The nation takes over the state,

00:04:38.490 --> 00:04:39.750
the state takes over the education,

00:04:39.750 --> 00:04:42.240
the education takes over the kids

00:04:42.240 --> 00:04:43.650
and then the kids believe the things

00:04:43.650 --> 00:04:47.040
which are commonsensical and
99 times out of a hundred

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:48.240
and I say this as a historian

00:04:48.240 --> 00:04:51.030
who gets trapped in cocktail
parties all the time in corners

00:04:51.030 --> 00:04:53.280
with people who know what
really happened in the past,

00:04:53.280 --> 00:04:56.970
99 times out of a hundred,
you never break free, right?

00:04:56.970 --> 00:04:58.050
99 times out of a hundred,

00:04:58.050 --> 00:05:00.750
you're basically trapped
where they pinned you down

00:05:00.750 --> 00:05:01.750
when you were seven.

00:05:03.990 --> 00:05:08.190
The less obvious way that the
nation gets hold of the past

00:05:08.190 --> 00:05:10.800
has to do not with the institutions,

00:05:10.800 --> 00:05:12.840
but with the form of the story.

00:05:12.840 --> 00:05:14.940
And I'm gonna tell you a
couple forms of the story

00:05:14.940 --> 00:05:17.670
and try to make them
seem less commonsensical

00:05:17.670 --> 00:05:20.580
or less obvious, less
natural than they are.

00:05:20.580 --> 00:05:23.340
I called this maybe a
little bit too preciously,

00:05:23.340 --> 00:05:25.800
I called this lecture
The Genesis of Nations,

00:05:25.800 --> 00:05:28.680
because now I'm gonna talk about Genesis.

00:05:28.680 --> 00:05:31.500
A great story about the nation

00:05:31.500 --> 00:05:35.010
is that there once was innocence
and the innocence was lost.

00:05:35.010 --> 00:05:36.990
That is a big story about the nation,

00:05:36.990 --> 00:05:40.380
especially nations that
emerge out of empires.

00:05:40.380 --> 00:05:42.768
Especially nations like the Russian.

00:05:42.768 --> 00:05:44.610
I'm not gonna talk about
too much about America,

00:05:44.610 --> 00:05:46.140
but it's certainly true of America too.

00:05:46.140 --> 00:05:47.910
There's an American imperial story

00:05:47.910 --> 00:05:50.310
about how things were at some point,

00:05:50.310 --> 00:05:53.250
the 1920s, 1930s, 1940s, 1950s.

00:05:53.250 --> 00:05:54.960
At some point, things were fine.

00:05:54.960 --> 00:05:56.790
At some point, things were good.

00:05:56.790 --> 00:06:00.360
And then somehow the immigrants
got in and we lost control

00:06:00.360 --> 00:06:01.950
and now things aren't so good.

00:06:01.950 --> 00:06:04.170
That's a story of innocence.

00:06:04.170 --> 00:06:05.940
If you're about making
the country great again,

00:06:05.940 --> 00:06:06.900
like a cycle.

00:06:06.900 --> 00:06:08.910
You go back to a cycle
where there's a point

00:06:08.910 --> 00:06:11.400
or the founders are another
good example of this.

00:06:11.400 --> 00:06:14.913
So some people think that
the moment of 1776 or 1789

00:06:14.913 --> 00:06:17.400
is a kind of moment of innocence.

00:06:17.400 --> 00:06:19.350
The founders got it basically right.

00:06:19.350 --> 00:06:21.270
That's a very attractive idea.

00:06:21.270 --> 00:06:22.530
The founders thought of everything,

00:06:22.530 --> 00:06:23.580
they're kind of demigods.

00:06:23.580 --> 00:06:26.790
They walk the earth, leaving
huge footprints behind them

00:06:26.790 --> 00:06:28.500
and the footprints were
filled with the water

00:06:28.500 --> 00:06:29.790
and residue of righteousness.

00:06:29.790 --> 00:06:31.050
And that's all you have to know.

00:06:31.050 --> 00:06:33.000
That's a very attractive view.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:35.460
Somebody got everything right
at one point in time.

00:06:35.460 --> 00:06:37.260
Most of the Supreme Court now

00:06:37.260 --> 00:06:39.243
pretends to believe this at this point.

00:06:40.410 --> 00:06:43.530
By the way, you know what the
problem with originalism is?

00:06:43.530 --> 00:06:44.880
I realize this is not our subject at all

00:06:44.880 --> 00:06:45.870
so you don't have to take notes.

00:06:45.870 --> 00:06:48.660
But there's a school of
thought called originalism

00:06:48.660 --> 00:06:50.250
about the American Constitution,

00:06:50.250 --> 00:06:53.100
which says that you have
to take the Constitution

00:06:53.100 --> 00:06:55.320
only in terms of what it actually says.

00:06:55.320 --> 00:06:58.050
But you know what the
Constitution doesn't say?

00:06:58.050 --> 00:06:59.940
It doesn't say that you have
to take the Constitution

00:06:59.940 --> 00:07:01.440
the way that the
Constitution actually says.

00:07:01.440 --> 00:07:03.360
That is to say the originalist position

00:07:03.360 --> 00:07:05.520
is self-contradictory
because the originalist position

00:07:05.520 --> 00:07:07.893
is not actually in the
Constitution, right?

00:07:09.180 --> 00:07:10.830
Okay. I've blown your minds, right?

00:07:10.830 --> 00:07:13.860
All right.
(students laughing)

00:07:13.860 --> 00:07:16.320
But I'm only saying this by way

00:07:16.320 --> 00:07:20.130
of this general imperial nation problem

00:07:20.130 --> 00:07:22.170
of wanting to go back to a moment

00:07:22.170 --> 00:07:24.360
where somehow we got everything right.

00:07:24.360 --> 00:07:27.240
In Russia today, this is very evident

00:07:27.240 --> 00:07:31.473
in the thought of a
character called Ivan Ilyin,

00:07:35.250 --> 00:07:37.120
who for several years Putin read

00:07:38.040 --> 00:07:43.040
and who takes a view like
this, that the world is flawed.

00:07:44.187 --> 00:07:49.187
The world itself is flawed, but
Russia has a kind of mission

00:07:49.620 --> 00:07:53.163
of restoring the innocence of the world.

00:07:54.203 --> 00:07:55.830
I mean, it's kind of ironic,

00:07:55.830 --> 00:07:57.930
but very often it's the imperial nations,

00:07:57.930 --> 00:08:00.630
the post-imperial nations
that are focused on innocence.

00:08:00.630 --> 00:08:03.173
They're focused on a time
when everything was all right.

00:08:04.470 --> 00:08:06.780
Nations that are peripheral

00:08:06.780 --> 00:08:09.720
or are anti-colonial, anti-imperial

00:08:09.720 --> 00:08:12.240
very often have a different
structure of story,

00:08:12.240 --> 00:08:13.890
which I wanna try to make seem

00:08:13.890 --> 00:08:15.780
both familiar and
unfamiliar to you if I can.

00:08:15.780 --> 00:08:20.780
And that's a three part story.
And again, it's biblical.

00:08:21.330 --> 00:08:23.790
So the story of lost
innocence is of course,

00:08:23.790 --> 00:08:25.800
the story of Adam and
Eve, the garden of Eden.

00:08:25.800 --> 00:08:29.160
There's also a longer
story in the Hebrew Bible,

00:08:29.160 --> 00:08:33.540
the Old Testament about a
people which had a state,

00:08:33.540 --> 00:08:35.490
but then that mistakes were made

00:08:35.490 --> 00:08:38.490
or bad people came and
they lost their state.

00:08:38.490 --> 00:08:40.980
But at some point they're
gonna get their state back.

00:08:40.980 --> 00:08:42.210
And when they get their state back,

00:08:42.210 --> 00:08:43.762
everything's gonna be fine.

00:08:43.762 --> 00:08:48.210
That's a structural story
that's inside the Bible.

00:08:48.210 --> 00:08:49.140
People have different views

00:08:49.140 --> 00:08:51.150
about how it's gonna be right again.

00:08:51.150 --> 00:08:54.120
The Christians say Jesus came
and then everything was fine.

00:08:54.120 --> 00:08:56.640
Zionists might say we made
Israel, then everything was fine.

00:08:56.640 --> 00:08:58.770
You can be in disagreement
about when everything is fine,

00:08:58.770 --> 00:09:01.290
but there's still the
basic three part story

00:09:01.290 --> 00:09:06.290
of everything was once good,
then we lost it somehow.

00:09:06.480 --> 00:09:08.760
Probably not our fault,
probably somebody else's fault,

00:09:08.760 --> 00:09:09.810
but we lost it.

00:09:09.810 --> 00:09:12.720
But then there will be
a moment of redemption.

00:09:12.720 --> 00:09:17.720
So the nation takes over
this story very easily.

00:09:17.730 --> 00:09:18.750
You've probably heard phrases

00:09:18.750 --> 00:09:23.703
like national renaissance, a rebirth.

00:09:24.750 --> 00:09:25.620
The whole idea of rebirth

00:09:25.620 --> 00:09:28.020
is if you think about
it just for a second,

00:09:28.020 --> 00:09:31.473
in some kind of literal
way, it's a very weird idea.

00:09:32.400 --> 00:09:33.233
It's very weird.

00:09:33.233 --> 00:09:35.760
If you just think for
a quarter of a second,

00:09:35.760 --> 00:09:37.170
what it would be like to be reborn,

00:09:37.170 --> 00:09:39.213
wouldn't that be strange, right?

00:09:40.830 --> 00:09:42.120
Okay, this may be a little too Freudian,

00:09:42.120 --> 00:09:43.743
you just left home, I know.

00:09:44.850 --> 00:09:46.950
But a rebirth is a strange idea

00:09:46.950 --> 00:09:48.400
if you think about it at all.

00:09:49.380 --> 00:09:51.480
So the idea of a national rebirth

00:09:51.480 --> 00:09:53.820
is that you're going back to that time

00:09:53.820 --> 00:09:55.560
when everything was right.

00:09:55.560 --> 00:09:58.200
You're going back to that golden age.

00:09:58.200 --> 00:10:00.780
Usually the nation says we're
in some kind of middle period

00:10:00.780 --> 00:10:01.980
where things have gone wrong,

00:10:01.980 --> 00:10:04.110
but everything used to be right.

00:10:04.110 --> 00:10:06.840
And if you're an anti-colonial
or a post-colonial nation,

00:10:06.840 --> 00:10:08.670
the story usually has
to do with the people.

00:10:08.670 --> 00:10:12.324
The people were right and good.

00:10:12.324 --> 00:10:14.850
They're still somehow
basically right and good

00:10:14.850 --> 00:10:17.190
and we're gonna restore
that rightness and goodness

00:10:17.190 --> 00:10:20.070
by giving them a state and
then things are gonna be fine.

00:10:20.070 --> 00:10:21.210
There's been a middle period,

00:10:21.210 --> 00:10:23.760
which involves a diaspora or an empire

00:10:23.760 --> 00:10:25.290
or something messing things up.

00:10:25.290 --> 00:10:27.450
But in the future,
things are gonna be good.

00:10:27.450 --> 00:10:29.700
So notice the three part story.

00:10:29.700 --> 00:10:33.300
The three part story is very
widespread. Very widespread.

00:10:33.300 --> 00:10:35.940
Classical examples are
the Jewish national story,

00:10:35.940 --> 00:10:37.980
the Greek national story.

00:10:37.980 --> 00:10:40.350
And I mentioned in the last
lecture, the Jews and Greeks

00:10:40.350 --> 00:10:42.240
are actually the oldest
documented inhabitants

00:10:42.240 --> 00:10:43.890
of the territory of Ukraine.

00:10:43.890 --> 00:10:45.750
But basically, every national story

00:10:45.750 --> 00:10:49.720
has cottoned onto this,
has followed this pattern.

00:10:52.320 --> 00:10:54.150
So I'm gonna say the obvious thing now.

00:10:54.150 --> 00:10:56.280
It's not that this is true.

00:10:56.280 --> 00:10:58.410
It's not that there
ever was a pure nation.

00:10:58.410 --> 00:11:00.270
It's not that there was an ethnicity

00:11:00.270 --> 00:11:02.790
which existed a thousand years
ago and still exists today.

00:11:02.790 --> 00:11:04.380
I hope I'm not shattering
anybody's illusions,

00:11:04.380 --> 00:11:06.993
but that never actually happens.

00:11:09.120 --> 00:11:12.870
I know I'm breaking something to you now,

00:11:12.870 --> 00:11:14.340
but somebody has to at some point.

00:11:14.340 --> 00:11:17.433
Relationships are a lot more
complicated than that, right?

00:11:18.420 --> 00:11:20.220
Fatherhood and motherhood and sex.

00:11:20.220 --> 00:11:22.320
It's a lot more complicated
than a straight line

00:11:22.320 --> 00:11:24.150
from a thousand years to now.

00:11:24.150 --> 00:11:27.748
Okay. I'm glad we had this moment.

00:11:27.748 --> 00:11:30.720
I feel like this awkwardness
has now been dealt with.

00:11:30.720 --> 00:11:31.833
Okay, good.

00:11:34.020 --> 00:11:35.940
So I'm not gonna surprise you

00:11:35.940 --> 00:11:38.010
when I say that that's not
how history actually works.

00:11:38.010 --> 00:11:39.960
There isn't really a three part.

00:11:39.960 --> 00:11:43.140
There isn't really a golden
age, diaspora return to gold.

00:11:43.140 --> 00:11:44.910
That doesn't really happen.

00:11:44.910 --> 00:11:48.870
But the story is reflecting something.

00:11:48.870 --> 00:11:51.210
It's reflecting a change
that is happening.

00:11:51.210 --> 00:11:55.290
It's a way of handling a
change which is happening.

00:11:55.290 --> 00:12:00.290
And that change is the entrance
of the people into politics.

00:12:01.500 --> 00:12:05.040
So the nation and the way
we're talking about the nation

00:12:05.040 --> 00:12:07.350
is a modern form of politics,

00:12:07.350 --> 00:12:09.090
which involves, if not everybody,

00:12:09.090 --> 00:12:11.340
it's meant to involve the masses.

00:12:11.340 --> 00:12:12.900
It's not feudalism.

00:12:12.900 --> 00:12:15.120
It's not the nobility
being in charge, right?

00:12:15.120 --> 00:12:19.020
It's not monarchy, it's not
aristocracy, it's not oligarchy,

00:12:19.020 --> 00:12:20.730
it's not rule by the few.

00:12:20.730 --> 00:12:22.530
The nation means rule by the many.

00:12:22.530 --> 00:12:23.790
Doesn't necessarily mean democracy,

00:12:23.790 --> 00:12:25.920
but the nation means a form of politics

00:12:25.920 --> 00:12:28.200
in which the subject of politics

00:12:28.200 --> 00:12:31.409
is supposed to be the people.

00:12:31.409 --> 00:12:34.380
That's an idea which seems
very commonsensical now.

00:12:34.380 --> 00:12:35.910
I mean, even the people who are against it

00:12:35.910 --> 00:12:38.550
say that they're for it
as you might have noticed.

00:12:38.550 --> 00:12:40.950
Basically everybody in the world,

00:12:40.950 --> 00:12:43.351
as they do away with democracy,
they talk about how, yes,

00:12:43.351 --> 00:12:45.360
the only way to have democracy

00:12:45.360 --> 00:12:47.060
is to suppress all of these votes.

00:12:48.270 --> 00:12:50.220
Only if I count the votes
it's a demo-- you know.

00:12:50.220 --> 00:12:53.700
But very rarely people say,
oh, I'm against democracy.

00:12:53.700 --> 00:12:56.910
It's commonsensical. But
that's very new, right?

00:12:56.910 --> 00:12:59.520
The idea that the people
are the subject of politics

00:12:59.520 --> 00:13:01.749
is only a couple hundred years old.

00:13:01.749 --> 00:13:06.749
So these stories are a way
of handling a transformation.

00:13:06.840 --> 00:13:08.640
They're a way of handling change.

00:13:08.640 --> 00:13:10.860
So now I'm moving from what
they say about themselves

00:13:10.860 --> 00:13:12.870
to how they actually work.

00:13:12.870 --> 00:13:14.280
The reason that they actually work

00:13:14.280 --> 00:13:18.330
is that in the 19th century,
let's say, more or less,

00:13:18.330 --> 00:13:21.150
there comes a time when you have to handle

00:13:21.150 --> 00:13:25.500
a form of politics in which
the people now matter,

00:13:25.500 --> 00:13:27.540
large numbers of people now matter.

00:13:27.540 --> 00:13:30.720
And so you need some version of the past

00:13:30.720 --> 00:13:32.310
which accounts for that.

00:13:32.310 --> 00:13:34.740
And the version of the
past that you can give

00:13:34.740 --> 00:13:38.010
is the one that says way back when,

00:13:38.010 --> 00:13:39.600
the people were in charge

00:13:39.600 --> 00:13:41.730
and now the people are
gonna be in charge again.

00:13:41.730 --> 00:13:44.070
Or way back when, the people were virtuous

00:13:44.070 --> 00:13:46.380
and now they're gonna be virtuous again

00:13:46.380 --> 00:13:49.170
once we do away with the
empire or the diaspora

00:13:49.170 --> 00:13:51.030
or one of the things which was in the way

00:13:51.030 --> 00:13:52.440
of this pattern from happening.

00:13:52.440 --> 00:13:56.160
So the story is a way of
making sense of something,

00:13:56.160 --> 00:13:59.610
making sense of a challenge,
which actually had to be met.

00:13:59.610 --> 00:14:01.710
And the challenge is what do you do

00:14:01.710 --> 00:14:03.450
as the people enter politics?

00:14:03.450 --> 00:14:05.760
That's a challenge which was
met in all kinds of other ways.

00:14:05.760 --> 00:14:08.190
Like the Marxists who we're
still gonna talk about

00:14:08.190 --> 00:14:10.650
met the challenge in a certain way.

00:14:10.650 --> 00:14:13.470
So the people are entering politics,

00:14:13.470 --> 00:14:15.420
there is some kind of transformation.

00:14:15.420 --> 00:14:16.863
And I want you to mark this.

00:14:18.120 --> 00:14:19.800
We'll get to this part of the
course here in a few weeks,

00:14:19.800 --> 00:14:23.340
but think about what is changing.

00:14:23.340 --> 00:14:26.850
Is it that there's now
a big capitalist economy

00:14:26.850 --> 00:14:29.640
and so people are encountering
each other in new ways.

00:14:29.640 --> 00:14:32.940
Is it that there's now a functional state,

00:14:32.940 --> 00:14:34.440
which is able to collect taxes

00:14:34.440 --> 00:14:36.750
and make people perform military service.

00:14:36.750 --> 00:14:39.570
These are some of the
changes that are associated

00:14:39.570 --> 00:14:41.310
with modernization.

00:14:41.310 --> 00:14:43.260
But something is changing

00:14:43.260 --> 00:14:46.283
so that it no longer seems normal to say

00:14:46.283 --> 00:14:49.430
that the king is just in charge

00:14:49.430 --> 00:14:51.060
or the nobility is just in charge.

00:14:51.060 --> 00:14:52.500
Something is changing so that

00:14:52.500 --> 00:14:55.380
that no longer seems plausible.

00:14:55.380 --> 00:14:57.900
There's still kings and queens,

00:14:57.900 --> 00:15:00.690
but they basically serve as
the kind of rhetorical cover

00:15:00.690 --> 00:15:02.089
for welfare states.

00:15:02.089 --> 00:15:04.923
They're not what they used to be.

00:15:07.650 --> 00:15:11.197
Fascinating as they are, the
adventures of Harry and Meghan,

00:15:11.197 --> 00:15:15.423
that's not what royalty used to be like.

00:15:16.320 --> 00:15:18.060
It was a little like that,

00:15:18.060 --> 00:15:20.970
but that was never the essence of it.

00:15:20.970 --> 00:15:24.480
So at a certain point, it
stopped seeming plausible

00:15:24.480 --> 00:15:25.860
that a few people should be in charge

00:15:25.860 --> 00:15:26.970
and how do you handle that?

00:15:26.970 --> 00:15:28.773
Well, you handle that with a story.

00:15:30.450 --> 00:15:33.330
So you have modern politics

00:15:33.330 --> 00:15:36.060
and modern politics has to have a story

00:15:36.060 --> 00:15:39.120
about how the people are
coming into politics,

00:15:39.120 --> 00:15:40.950
why the people should come into politics.

00:15:40.950 --> 00:15:43.560
And this story is
displacing other stories.

00:15:43.560 --> 00:15:44.910
Okay, here comes question time.

00:15:44.910 --> 00:15:46.500
What's another story?

00:15:46.500 --> 00:15:49.500
What kind of story would
that have been displacing?

00:15:49.500 --> 00:15:51.750
What's a story that
would've made sense? Yeah.

00:15:51.750 --> 00:15:53.310
- [Student] So a king is chosen

00:15:53.310 --> 00:15:55.560
by some religious, like God, right?

00:15:55.560 --> 00:15:58.170
Now I'm the king and I control society.

00:15:58.170 --> 00:16:00.270
- Yeah, okay. So divine right.

00:16:00.270 --> 00:16:02.880
Or you're the king,
